participants.participant: Karen A. Fletcher, Vice President, Investor Relations
Ellen J. Kullman, Chief Executive Officer
Jeffrey L. Keefer, Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer
Nicholas C. Fanandakis, Senior Vice President

plist.p: Good morning. My name is John and I will be your conference operator today. At this time, I'd like to welcome to you the DuPont 2009 Third Quarter Earnings Call. All lines have been placed on mute to prevent any background noise. After the speakers' remarks, there will be a question-and-answer period. To listen to the webcast, please go to www.dupont.com. Thank you.
It is now my pleasure to turn the floor over to your host, Karen Fletcher, Vice President of Investor Relations. Ma'am, you may begin your conference.

Thank you, John. Good morning and welcome. With me this morning are Ellen Kullman, CEO, Jeff Keefer, CFO, and Nick Fanandakis, CFO designate. The slides for today's call can be found on our website at dupont.com along with the news release that was issued earlier today.

Please turn to slide two. During the course of this conference call, we will make forward-looking statements. All statements that address expectations or projections about the future are forward-looking statements. Although they reflect our current expectations, these statements are not guarantees of future performance, but involve a number of risks and assumptions. We urge you to review DuPont's SEC filings for a discussion of some of the factors that could cause actual results to differ materially. We will also refer to non-GAAP measures and request that you please refer to the reconciliation to GAAP statement provided with our earnings news release and on our website.
And finally, we have posted supplemental information on our website that we hope is helpful to your understanding of our company's performance.
With that I'll turn the call over to Ellen.

Good morning. First of all, let me say, I'm pleased with our third quarter earnings performance in which aggressive cost productivity results are clearly evident, coupled with higher sequential sales for most of our industrial businesses. Company sales this quarter excluding ag are up 11% on a sequential basis. The underlying demand signal that is emerging reflects a developing recovery that is shaped differently by market and by geography.

Let me touch on a few areas where early signs of recovery are becoming more clear. DuPont titanium dioxide is approaching a sold out position. Our coatings and polymer products experienced strong demand in response to increases in motor vehicle production. And engineering polymer products experienced an additional boost from restocking demands across their automotive supply chains in the quarter.

From a regional perspective, Asia-Pacific year-over-year comparison was encouraging, with sales only down 5%. On a closer look, China sales were up 7% year-over-year and sales in India, Singapore, and Vietnam were down just a few percent. U.S. and European markets are showing some signs of improvement but are clearly lagging behind Asia.

On the other hand, our aramids business, which includes Nomex and Kevlar, was late heading into the downturn and lagged into the third quarter. Demand for aramid products was weak in the third quarter with more destocking occurring than we had expected coming into the quarter. More recent sales trends indicate demand for Kevlar is turning up, though.

Our ag and nutrition sales were down 5% due in part to weather and lower corn acreage in Latin America. Seed sales were up 7% over last year, helped in part by strong sales of Y series soybeans. We anticipate great yield performance from this new family of products once the harvest data is in.

Sales of Rynaxypyr insecticide are about 140 million year-to-date, indicating that we will easily surpass our sales target of 150 million and be closer to 200 million this year which is the second year of launch. The success of Rynaxypyr is an outstanding example of how we identify a market need, developed a family of products with exceptional performance, and are meeting with enthusiastic response from customers around the world.

Stepping back for a broader view of DuPont's market driven science at work, we launched 323 new products in the quarter, bringing our year-to-date total to 1107 or almost 50% more than the first three quarters of 2008. I am pleased that our businesses continue to seize every opportunity in today's difficult environment to bring value to customers using new products to help them differentiate their own offerings in the marketplace.

Another example of how we're putting new products to work is in the photovoltaics market. After a slow start to the year, we're seeing a rebound in PV markets in the second half. While the 2009 market will likely end up flat versus 2008, we expect our sales to be up over 10% this year. We believe annual growth rates will return to more historic levels of around 30% annual growth starting next year. And we're focused on delivering a constant stream of product innovation and value.

PV customers have aggressive cost reduction targets to meet as well as greater environmental responsibilities. And we recently introduced a new generation of Solamet metallization paste that contributes to a solar module with a significantly reduced environmental footprint. These pastes meet high product performance requirements without requiring the use of materials such as lead or cadmium containing glasses.

We also partnered with a company in the thin film manufacturing to develop a Solamet product for modules that require low temperature processing and therefore, lower production costs. These are examples of market-driven science in action.

Turning to productivity, fixed costs, we delivered 900 million in savings through the third quarter and are closing in on our $1 billion goal for the year. We remain vigilant about keeping about 750 million of these cost reductions out long-term. Our shareholders should expect continued cost productivity from DuPont beyond 2009.

All in, this was a very good quarter where our employees delivered on four key priorities: excellent pricing discipline, new product innovation, cost productivity and overall strong execution. I'll have more to say on these topics at our investor event in Wilmington scheduled for two weeks from today.

Before I turn the call over to Jeff, I want to mention our new organizational structure, which we announced in August. It took effect October 1, and it's aimed at driving decision-making closer to our customers with greater regional accountability within our businesses. We took out a layer of management and consolidated a number of business units. Each business has clear accountability for earnings and cash management and a clear mission to enable DuPont to deliver sustainable earnings growth. Beginning with the fourth quarter, we will report results for seven financial reporting units.
Now I'll turn the call over to Jeff.

Thanks, Ellen. Good morning, everyone. DuPont had a strong third quarter, and I confidently echo Ellen on the specific commitments we're on track to deliver: pricing for value, cost and capital productivity, generating cash, and finishing the year with a strong balance sheet. The actions on cost and pricing are creating strong operating leverage as demonstrated in our early cycle businesses' performance despite lower volumes.

The quarter contained two items I want to highlight. First item is lower raw material cost; while fourth quarter will show lower raw material costs versus prior year, we estimate that these costs bottomed in the third quarter, in effect shifting a few cents per share to the third quarter from the fourth. Secondly, a one-time benefit of four to five cents from a lower base tax rate this quarter compared to our guidance of 26% which I will detail out in a few minutes. After accounting for the tax benefit, still a very, very solid quarter.

Turning now to slide three, which summarizes earnings per share and sales results. Third quarter reported and underlying earnings per share were $0.45; excluding significant items from the third quarter of 2008, earnings per share were down 20% from the prior year. Consolidated net sales of $6 billion were down 18% compared to prior year, reflecting 12% volume decline, 3% unfavorable currency, 2% price decline and 1% sales reduction from portfolio changes. Excluding sales into agriculture end markets, segment volumes were down year-over-year about 15%.

Early in September, we updated investors showcasing the tremendous strengths of titanium dioxide. This is an early cycle product. On slide four the data depict our year-over-year sales variances, showing measured and visibly improving divisions. As a contrast Nomex and Kevlar, which are a significant portion of safety and protection revenue, are late cycle products and are lagging our early cycle by several months.

Turning to slide five and looking at the sales variance by segment. Karen will cover all of the detail in a moment, but I would – want to make a few comments on prices, so that there is no confusion. First, all businesses are showing a negative currency impact in price ranging anywhere from 1 to 5%. In addition, Electronic & Communication Technologies' price decline primarily reflects metals pass-through effects. Safety & Protection reflects the chemicals businesses, which have contractual commodity pass-through as well as mix shift from aramids to chemicals. Performance Materials is affected by a mix shift towards less specialty applications in our packaging segment.

While markets are very competitive, we have not seen broad based price decreases. In some cases, businesses have raised price based on new products or other dynamics specific to their local market conditions. The bottom line, pricing overall is about as expected. This combined with aggressive cost productivity has resulted in margin expansion in Coatings & Color Technologies, Performance Materials and Electronic & Communications Technologies versus same period last year.

Moving to slide six for a review of sales by region, two areas to highlight. Asia results show the most favorable improvement in the rate of decline. Sales of $1.4 billion were down 5% versus the same period last year, reflecting both volume and price declines. Our businesses are seeing a quarter-over-quarter improvement in volume. We move from a 31% volume decline in the first quarter to volumes being down about 3% in the third quarter. China sales are leading the region's recovery. Our sales in China were $520 million, up 7% in the third quarter versus the same period last year, with our Electronics product sales up about 18%. In contrast, European volumes are still the most challenged. Emerging Europe volumes are down about half that of developed Europe. Our sales in Europe were $1.6 billion, down 27%.

Turning now to the third quarter, earnings per share variance analysis versus prior year on slide seven. The quarter showed a net benefit of $0.30 reflecting the spread between price and variable cost excluding the impacts of currency and volume.

Variable costs decreased year-over-year in all segments excluding Agriculture and Nutrition. As I mentioned at the opening, the forecasting of the timing of raw material flow through is difficult due to the change in purchasing patterns, contract – contract sales patterns and continued volatility of commodity prices.

The results in the third quarter outpaced our expectations somewhat, but have not significantly changed our view for the full year. We are narrowing the outlook range for 2009 to about 5 to 6% decline, excluding currency and volume. We anticipate year-over-year raw material cost declines will continue to roll through in the fourth quarter, but we expect that the largest delta will have been realized in the third quarter.

Looking at volume impact on earnings, the 12% volume decline resulted in an earnings reduction of $0.32 per share compared to the same period previous year. In addition, related low capacity utilization resulted in a reduction of about $0.03 per share. With the increased volumes, this charge is down about $0.06 versus the second quarter. Our demand outlook for the fourth quarter is for improved volumes year-over-year, noting that the fourth quarter of 2008 marked the start of tremendous demand disruption and inventory destocking.

Moving now to fixed costs. Excluding currency and volume, fixed cost was a net benefit of $0.04 per share in the quarter. Non-cash pension costs of about $0.10 per share and continued growth investments particularly in Agriculture were more than offset by cost reductions from the vast array of restructuring and productivity actions we have taken. The estimated benefit in the quarter of our cost reduction programs was about $300 million in savings. On a year-to-date basis that puts us at $900 million reductions and we are on track to meet the target of $1 billion. All of the businesses across the globe stepped up to this challenge and established processes to deliver reductions in 2009 as well as to reset the cost structure for the long-term.
At our November 3rd investor event, we will outline our planned productivity efforts.

Turning now to currency. Year-over-year, currency reduced earnings per share by about $0.06, reflecting about a 9% stronger dollar based on our sales weighted currency. Assuming currencies hold around the current levels, we expect fourth quarter benefit to essentially net out the third quarter impact. Other on the waterfall reduced earnings by $0.02 a share reflecting higher net interest of $0.02 and offsetting impacts of an other income headwind of $0.03 and an exchange gain and loss benefit of $0.03.

Our base tax rate was 18.1% versus 14.4% same period prior year, creating a $0.02 headwind. As discussed in my opening comments, the base tax rate created about a 0.04 to $0.05 benefit versus our previous guidance of about 26%. Favorable geographic mix of earnings has resulted in a reduced full-year forecasted base tax rate to a range of 24 to 25% which created a current quarter benefit.

I wanted to highlight the difference between our third quarter base tax rate of 18.1% and the effective tax rate of negative 5.9%. The difference in rate is caused by taxes generated from our balance sheet hedging program we refer to as exchange gain (loss), or EGL. When the tax benefit of EGL is matched with the pre-tax loss of 128 million, the quarter-over-quarter impact of exchange gain and loss is a 3% – $0.03 benefit and included in other on the waterfall. We have provided more detail on Schedule D to show you the exact impact our hedging program had on our effective tax rate.

Turning now to the balance sheet and cash on slide eight. Third quarter free cash flow was an inflow of $607 million compared to an inflow of 413 million in the same period last year. The increase within the quarter reflects lower cash flow from operations more than offset by lower capital expenditures.

Working capital is down versus same period last year reflecting in part a $1.2 billion reduction in inventory. Each quarter this year we have differentiated capital spending by business based on their evolving business environment. We continue to support growth areas of agriculture and nutrition, applied bioscience and photovoltaics while aligning capital spend with the level of demand in other businesses. We expect to meet our target of 1.4 billion, a 30% year-over-year reduction.

Regarding dividends. To date, DuPont stock is yielding about 5%. With the dividend payment in September, we have paid 420 consecutive dividends. Our forecast for free cash flow remains $2.5 billion reflecting a strong cash generation in the fourth quarter.

So in summary, based on the way the quarter's successfully unfolded we are narrowing earnings guidance towards the upper end of our previous range to $1.95 to $2.05 per share. We feel good about the accomplishments so far in 2009 and the solid basis put into place for improved operating leverage for 2010 and beyond. We look forward to outlining our growth plans for 2010 and beyond in our upcoming investor event on November 3rd. Now I'll turn it over to Karen for a review of the segments. Karen?

Thanks, Jeff. Turning to slide nine, Ag & Nutrition revenues of $1.2 billion were down 5% on lower industry volumes and unfavorable currency, partly offset by Ag market share gains and seed price. The seasonal pre-tax operating loss of $113 million reflected lower sales, higher costs and the absence of a $49 million gain from closing soybean contracts in the third quarter 2008. While segment fixed costs increased modestly due to continued strategic growth investments in seed research and our global sales force and to seed inventory adjustments, food and nutrition products realized another quarter of improved cost productivity performance.

Let's take a closer look at the results from our crop protection products group. Revenue declined modestly, impacted primarily by glyphosate price and high channel inventory, cereal herbicide volumes and unfavorable currency, partly offset by fungicide price and volume and global Rynaxypyr sales.

Earnings were down substantially off of a seasonally small base due to lower glyphosate market price, soft industry volumes and unfavorable currency, partly offset by higher selling prices across the remainder of the portfolio and fixed cost productivity.

For the fourth quarter, we expect crop protection product sales to be up moderately on demand for North American soybean herbicides, European cereal herbicides, Latin America fungicides and insecticides, Asia-Pacific Rynaxypyr sales and favorable currency, partly offset by lower prices.

Pre-tax operating losses are projected to be essentially flat with higher volumes and favorable currency being offset by price and higher business fixed costs associated with increased Rynaxypyr sales given new registrations in Japan and Brazil.

Turning to seeds, sales increased 7% to $471 million, reflecting higher prices from strong product performance and technology sales in Brazil and strong in-season sales in North America. Seasonal pre-tax operating losses increased substantially, reflecting the third quarter 2008 soybean gain and the contract settlement I mentioned earlier, reduced corn planting area in the Southern Hemisphere, continued investments in R&D and sales force expansion and unfavorable currency.

Looking ahead to the fourth quarter, we expect seed sales to be up substantially on strong global sales, favorable currency and international price gains. As is typical for fourth quarter, with seasonal sales against the period's full complement of fixed costs, we expect to have a pre-tax operating loss. Seed earnings are expected to improve substantially, reflecting expected market share gains associated with Latin America summer and early safrinha corn sales, early North America corn and soybean sales, Africa and Asia-Pacific sales and early Europe corn sales, and international price and favorable currency, partly offset by base cost of goods sold and growth investments.

So for the full year 2009 Ag and Nutrition segment outlook, we expect the segment to deliver mid-single digit sales growth and pre-tax operating income growth of at least 10%, or more than 30% if you exclude currency, over 2008.

Despite significant effective currency, which we anticipate will be about a $350 million impact to sales in 2009, we're on track with our compounded annual earnings growth rate of more than 15% over the time period 2007 through 2013.

Now let's turn to slide 10 and Coatings & Color Technologies. Sales of $1.5 billion were down 16%, primarily reflecting continued weakness in motor vehicle markets. Pre-tax operating income of $182 million was 4% lower, reflecting lower sales volumes and unfavorable currency partly offset by lower variable costs – fixed cost reductions and pricing gains. Titanium dioxide product sales declined moderately driven primarily by volume. Earnings were up modestly with lower raw material costs and fixed cost reductions partly offset by reduced demand.

Coatings sales declined significantly year-over-year reflecting a corresponding decline in motor vehicle sales. However, this drop in revenue was the smallest quarterly drop this year as auto builds grew moderately sequentially in most regions. North American motor vehicle production was down 19% versus prior year quarter, and European motor vehicle production was down 15%. Refinished paint products volume dropped significantly, driven by continued weakness in global economic conditions. Coatings earnings were down modestly, driven by declines in volume and unfavorable currency partly offset by lower raw material costs and lower fixed costs.

Looking ahead to the fourth quarter for this segment, we expect sales to be flat sequentially and moderately up year-over-year. Demand assumptions reflect the following: First, that global motor vehicle production levels will modestly increase on a sequential basis. Second, that global demand for titanium dioxide products will slightly decrease sequentially in line with seasonal patterns. And finally, that lower demand of re-finished paint products will be driven by normal seasonal patterns. As a result, we expect earnings to be up in the fourth quarter versus prior year with essentially flat earnings sequentially. Our team continues to be focused on delivering productivity improvements in costs and capital.

Please turn to slide 11 for Electronic & Communication Technologies segment. Sales of $919 million were down 13% compared to same period last year, reflecting 10% volume and 3% U.S dollar price decline. Sequentially, sales improved 16%, attributable to increased demand in photovoltaics, seasonality in consumer electronics and to a lesser extent specific downstream sales initiatives and displays.

Refrigerants experienced year-over-year and sequential volume declines. Continued growth in our HCFC replacement products, ISCEON and HFC blends, was more than offset by seasonal declines in refrigerants. Pre-tax earnings of $125 million reflects year-over-year volume declines, unfavorable currency impact and investment in photovoltaics, more than offsetting disciplined pricing, particularly in refrigerants and the lower benefit – the benefit of lower costs. Importantly, pre-tax operating margins were 40 basis points higher versus same period previous year.

For fourth quarter, the outlook anticipates sales and earnings growth year-over-year. Sequentially, sales and earnings are expected to be down, primarily reflecting seasonality that favored third quarter in electronics, refrigerants and fluoropolymer solutions.

Please turn to slide 12 for Performance Materials. Sales of $1.3 billion were down 24%, reflecting weak demand in major markets in all regions, particularly in general industrial and motor vehicle markets. As we indicated during last earnings call, we believe industry de-stocking was largely completed in the second quarter. Third quarter volumes appear to reflect true underlying demand with all regions showing sequential volume improvement versus second quarter. It was led by Asia, although North America, Western Europe and Latin America regions also showed improvement, particularly late in the quarter. Segment sales also benefited from Cash for Clunkers programs.

Pre-tax operating income of $230 million was up versus prior year earnings of $125 million, excluding hurricane related charges. The improvement also reflected lower costs, partly offset by lower sales volume, unfavorable product mix and currency. Current quarter includes $24 million of insurance recoveries related to Hurricane Ike claims.

Looking ahead to the fourth quarter, sequential sales are expected to be flat, reflecting seasonal pattern and unfavorable product mix. Earnings are expected to be down sequentially, reflecting higher raw material costs and the absence of a $24 million insurance recovery benefit in third quarter 2008, partly offset by fixed cost reductions. We expect more intense competitive pressure as additional competitor polymer capacity continues to come back online. The business teams continue to be focused on delivering strong cost productivity performance in the fourth quarter.

Turning to slide 13 and looking at Safety & Protection, sales of $1 billion were down 32%, reflecting a 22% volume decline, primarily in industrial and construction markets. Pricing decreases reflected the pass through of lower raw material costs. Pre-tax operating income of $93 million principally reflected lower market demand partly offset by lower raw material costs, fixed cost reductions and pricing actions. Current quarter includes a $26 million asset impairment charge.

For the fourth quarter, we anticipate sales to be down and earnings to be up year-over-year. Sequentially, sales and earnings are expected to be up driven by increased sequential demand with no further inventory de-stocking by customers and a slight improvement in underlying demand. Earnings should continue to benefit from lower raw material costs and fixed cost reductions.
So that completes our segment review, and now I'd like to welcome Nick to our call and turn things over to him.

Thanks, Karen. It's a pleasure to be here today. Our solid third quarter financial results along with our outlook say a tremendous amount about DuPont's ability to deliver against its commitments whatever the economic climate may be. Ellen and Jeff have established a solid foundation. By this I mean a corporate structure and processes that enable the company to focus on the fundamentals and deliver attractive results for our shareholders. Clearly, the year-to-date successes we've achieved are encouraging, but it's only the beginning of the big opportunities that lie ahead of us.

On November 3, we'll be hosting an investor event here at our headquarters in Wilmington, Delaware. On that day, our focus will be a long-term view of DuPont's growth prospects, as seen from the perspective of our new leadership team. Our innovation, coupled with the focused investments we have made, affords us some unique long-term opportunities. In addition, we'll provide insight into 2010, relating our long-term view to our short-term deliverables.

Finally, on a more personal note, I'd like to take this opportunity to thank Jeff for his leadership in the CFO role. He has displayed a winning combination of business experience, operational excellence, dedication to the company and perhaps most importantly, his innate ability to inspire individuals and motivate organizations. Jeff, I really look forward to building on the impressive foundation that you have laid.
And with that, I'll turn it back over to Ellen.

Thanks, Nick. In closing, I'd like to summarize our performance for the quarter. Volumes were down 12%, a significant improvement over the second quarter when volumes were down 19. We realized the biggest top line sequential improvements in Performance Materials, Coatings and Electronic business segments.

During this quarter, we saw the confluence of several factors that favored dramatic sequential margin improvement. Raw material prices finally appear to have hit the bottom line in full force; essentially they bottomed in this quarter. Our sales and marketing teams were able to hold prices reasonably intact and they seized opportunities to introduce new products with greater value for our customers. Benefits from aggressive fixed cost actions and restructuring paid off.

As for the fourth quarter, we anticipate sequential improvement in our industrial businesses, although we expect the trajectory to be erratic as supply chains are restocking and stabilizing to various degrees. Some markets like U.S. housing will take much longer than others to recover.

So against this backdrop of stabilization and early signs of recovery, we remain vigilant about the priorities that have enabled us to weather this storm and more importantly, will assure that we capitalize fully on a recovery. We are strong, focused and agile, and are delivering products that add value to customers and differentiate us from our competitors. Cost productivity is a way of life and we are determined to make 750 million of our fixed cost productivity permanent. And we will be disciplined as we invest our growth resources in markets where they are differentiated and can capture value from a competitive advantage, such as agriculture and alternate energy. And we're very well positioned to leverage our presence in emerging markets that we expect will return to growth as global recovery begins to take hold.
So on slide 14, you can see our 2009 directives, updated with progress through the third quarter. Simply stated, we're delivering against our commitments.

Before I close, I'd like to add my comments to Nick's and to thank Jeff. His leadership over the last three plus years, his wisdom, his guidance, his focus, his tenacity, I just look at Nick and say, "you've got big shoes to fill," but thank you, Jeff and Nick, we're really looking forward to working with you as CFO.
So with that I hope you'll be able to join us on November 3 and I look forward to seeing you then. And we're happy to take your questions.
Okay, John. So if you will just remind us of the instructions and open the line please.

Thank you, we will now begin the question-and-answer session. All line have been placed on mute to prevent any background noise. And our first question comes from Sergey Vasnetsov from Barclays Capital. Please go ahead.

Good morning. My question is a little bit more about next year. This year, fourth quarter typically as you said could be a little bit erratic, it's fairly weak and also we are already looking to 2010. What's your early view on 2010 in terms of earnings and also what's your view for the CapEx and growth?

Sergey, this is Jeff. We're going to lay all of that out for you on November 3, and so you get a comprehensive picture. What I'd comment on is, is that clearly we've laid a solid foundation for growth this year. We commented about pricing discipline, and our cost productivity is evident, and our new products, and so I think that bodes well for the future and the operating leverage of the company.
Okay. Thank you.
Our next question comes from Jeff Zekauskas from JPMorgan. Please go ahead.

Hi good morning. In the Performance Materials business you had a small gain but if we exclude the gain, you made about 200 million, and what I was wondering is, how sustainable is that level of EBIT in that your volumes are still way below the year ago period, you've cut out a lot of fixed costs, there's some puts and takes. Is that 200 million or so a normalized quarterly level now?

Jeff, this is Jeff again. Let me just – thank you for that question. Let me clarify. The Performance Materials platform has really put in a lot of productivity efforts and maintained disciplined pricing. I would point out that last year we did have the hurricane quarter over quarter which was an impact on the comparison. So you need to take that into account I think.
So did you just – I'm sorry, please.

No, I was just going to say Ed – Jeff, that we're really very well positioned by lowering our break even, our lower cost point. And I think you can expect double digit PTOI margins in the long term from that segment.

Okay. And then as my follow-up, one of the themes has been higher raw material costs in the agricultural area and obviously seed prices have been very, very volatile this year – or rather grain prices have been volatile. Is it the case that you get some raw material benefit in 2010 or can you not see that just yet?

Well, we're just harvesting the seed now. There's a lot of puts and takes to what that's going to be. Cost of goods sold will probably not be down as great given the lower commodity cost environment. But if we have very little carry over, I think we'll see a little bit. So that's hard to call because we're right in the middle of harvesting our seed, so we can, come on November 3 and we might – we'll have at least two weeks more information to be able to share with you.
Our next question comes from P.J. Juvekar from Citi. Please go ahead.

Yes, hi, good morning. If you take a look at your end markets: autos, housing, and others, can you tell us where you're seeing inventory restocking taking place? You mentioned autos but are there any other end markets where you're seeing that phenomena?

I think that in the electronics market we believe as we look down there that we've seen some of that in the third quarter as that Christmas season comes upon us. I think where we are as second or third tier in the automotive market, we've seen a little bit of that as well. But those are the two areas that I would say that we can clearly identify it versus just a base demand.
Okay. And then, in TiO2, you mentioned that it's a leading indicator and volumes are improving, are your price increases in that area sticking? Thank you.

Well, we have price increases out there right now. We're certainly seeing a tremendous amount of tightness in the environment. So we'll see as it comes. But I think the marketplace is – in a positive way would be supportive of it since, just look at ourselves, we're practically sold out.
Our next question comes from Mark Connelly from Sterne Agee. Please go ahead.

Hi, good morning. This is Ashish Gupta for Mark. I just wanted to ask about what's going on with – I know that pesticide demand has been off in some markets because of the good weather. But just curious why pricing hasn't held up as well. I know we saw pesticide prices moving up slowly when other ag inputs were on a tear. They looked pretty good even last quarter as other inputs had slowed. Should we just think about pesticide prices as lagging the rest of the ag inputs or is there something more specific?

Yes, Ashish. This is Karen. I think really what you're seeing is some of the influence of generics and a market that's been generally down due to weaker insect pressure, weaker fungicide needs. So in that kind of environment you're definitely seeing some competitive pricing pressure.
Great. Thank you.
Our next question comes from John Roberts from Buckingham Research. Please go ahead.
Morning.
Good morning, John.

You didn't provide any update on pharma, which – so I assume as we enter the transition period it's still relatively normal through year. I just want to check, are there any pipeline or inventory effects that might cause this to be nonlinear as we enter the transition period?

I would say, John, at this point, we'll guide to you fixed or flattish in the fourth quarter year-over-year, and when we have our event in two weeks, we're going to give you more color on pharma for 2010.

Okay. And then, as a follow-up on the raw materials, I think you were saying sequentially things have bottomed and will start to move up because of the lag with oil prices. Year-over-year in the fourth quarter, we still had a pretty big decline going on late last year. As we look year-over-year, we're also expecting that variable cost of $0.44 benefit to narrow materially as we go into the fourth quarter?

What I would say, John, is again, we still – for the full year, we still expect 5 to 6% lower raw material costs. Then if you'll recall in the first quarter, we were up about 5%, second quarter down about 5, third quarter down about 12 and as you remarked, we think it bottomed so we're expecting some uptick in the fourth quarter as a result of that. Still coming in at the same area we expected.
Our next question comes from David Begleiter from Deutsche Bank. Please go ahead.
Good morning. Ellen, you noted some pricing pressure in safety, performance, and electronics, given the bottoming of raws, do you expect some margin pressure going forward in those segments?

Well, I think if you dissect the price, first, you've got some pass through in metals, in electronics, and in chemicals, and safety and protection you have to account for. And the second thing is mix of business, especially in safety and protection with the late cycle of Kevlar and Nomex, that mix change in effect comes through on our price line. So we take a look at it and we dissect those as we go forward and the commodity pricing thing, that will be what it ends up to be. But I think it's through new products and the real focus on the customer that – and the discipline we put in will really help us get through this period.
Ellen, in the Ag segment, you call out further growth investments. Can you quantify those growth investments for '09 and what they will be in 2010, either up, down, or flat?

We'll defer '10 to the investor meeting. R&D as a percent of sales for this year is flat, but that means that we're spending more there, investing more in research and development. But we can take you through '10 in a little more detail in a couple weeks.
Our next question comes from Frank Mitsch from BB&T Capital Markets. Please go ahead.

Good morning. In terms of the cost reductions, you've been at a steady clip of 300 million a quarter up to 900 million at the end of the third quarter. And your target for 2009 was just a billion dollars. So a much slower progression for the fourth quarter is forecast. Internally, are you guys using a number higher than that in terms of cost reductions for the full year?

So, thanks for your question, Frank. I think this is one we wanted to make sure we covered. Last year, we started taking dramatic steps to slash fixed costs in the fourth quarter. If you just look at contractors, which was a big reduction for us, between September of '08 and the end of the year, we took out about 4,000 contractors as volumes fell across that period. So we had aggressive cost reduction in the fourth quarter. So on a year-over-year basis, it's not going to be as great as what we've seen because of the actions we took in the fourth quarter of 2008.
So the $1 billion dollar target is still our target.
So Frank, we're driving all of the actions there and we'll continue to and we'll tell you more about our productivity as we get together on November 3, and look out beyond – at 2010 and beyond.
All right, terrific. And you had indicated that I guess the fixed cost reductions were more than offsetting the non-cash pension expense. You expect that to continue in the fourth quarter as well?
Yes. Close, but yes.
Our next question comes from Mark Gulley for Soleil Securities. Please go ahead.

Yes. This has been talked about before. But I want to focus a little bit on pricing and cost. The appendix is always very helpful to us in looking at some of these trends. So on slide 16 we see chemical prices heading back up again, and of course your selling prices are still down on slide 18. So do we face the potential for margin squeeze here maybe coming up in the next several months?

It's interesting. If you look at the pattern as it flows through there is usually about a 30 day lag on the way up and on the way down. So – and that's something we've seen historically. So you know a squeeze would be very small from that standpoint.

Maybe just build on what Ellen said, remember the pricing declines that you're seeing this quarter is mostly due to pass-through and some mix shift. And looking at the top line, you know, we're going to continue to introduce new products. And we've talked with you before about the pricing tools we put into place in our businesses. So I feel pretty good about that whole thing. And we're about as expected for the year.
Yeah. And the comments around that kind of pressure would be strictly around electronics and chemicals where we have that pass through issue, not for the rest of the businesses.

Okay. That's helpful. We've talked a lot about your ambitious goals in ag and nutrition and a lot about seeds. But except for Rynaxypyr, are there any new crop protection chemical products that will help drive your growth?

Rynaxypyr has a young brother, Cyazypyr, that's coming out in a couple of years. We're going to be delineating out our growth prospects there in a couple of weeks so, you know, we feel very good especially in the insecticide area where we've got tremendous, a tremendous pipeline. That area's going to be about $1 billion by 2013 in revenue, so, good pipeline, get into more detail in a couple weeks.
Our next question comes from Robert Koort from Goldman Sachs. Please go ahead.

Thanks. Jeff, once more on the pricing and maybe we'll be beating it to death here but if I look at your charts, 16 and 18, so what you give for the benchmark industry prices and then your own prices, the last time you guys went negative at the end of a recession it was nine out of ten quarters you had declines year-on-year. Can you just give me some sense of that $0.14 hit, was the majority of that pass through stuff so that we shouldn't expect that same sort of performance over the next eight quarters that we might have seen at the beginning of the decade?

Yeah. Bob, great question. So again, most of it was pass through and mix as we kind of dissected and looked at this quarter. And I think we are very different from perhaps where we were at that point in time in terms of our capabilities that you commented on. And again, I'll come back to the new products. Ellen commented about how many we've put out this year, pricing for value as we've talked before is extremely important, we're doing well there.

And then our ability to put – or the capability we've put in around pricing, I think is really standing us in good stead. Really the ability through market segment and customer segmentation to do pinpoint pricing and understanding the profitability by product and customer and that's how we go about it. So I think we're in a different spot in terms of our capabilities and that'll bode well for us.

And then you gave PTOI or Karen talked about some expectations into the fourth quarter. I guess the biggest question mark I would see is in Pharma where you might have customers destocking that inventory channel ahead of, you know, generic competition. Can you give us some sense of what would be implied in your Pharma numbers for the fourth quarter?
I think Karen said about flat year-over-year, Bob.
Yeah. It's actually a very efficient supply chain. So we don't anticipate destocking this early Bob.
Our next question comes from Steve Schuman from Lafayette Research. Please go ahead.
Good morning.
Good morning.
You mentioned your ag seeds forecast is still on track for a multi-year 15%, is that still on track for 2009?

No. What we said was between 2007 and 2013 our entire ag platform will have greater than 15% compound annual growth rate on earnings. So for 2009, I think they might be on a little bit on the lower side of that. I mean it's going to average that over the period because of the things that we already talked about from a platform standpoint. But on the seed side, I think it will be – we're going to have a strong seed – strong year in the seed side. So I hope that helps answer your question, Steve.
Yeah. I guess on cash flow, cash flow's been very difficult this year. Do you think some of your cost savings are going to keep you from raising more debt next year with pharma going away?

No. We are not – again, we've got a very strong balance sheet and we're on plan to deliver the 2.5 billion of cash this year. I'm not anticipating any issues at all in terms of our funding capability.
And our next question comes from Peter Butler from Glen Hill Investment. Please go ahead.

Yeah, good morning. DuPont is waiting on some key approvals from the government on seeds and traits and on your previous conference call, you sounded pretty upbeat on getting some imminent approvals. Have there been delays? Could you handicap the prospects for some of the key approvals you're waiting on?
Thanks, Peter. In Optimum AcreMax, we expect the EPA decision to come in a matter of weeks. We're confident that we'll receive it, and get that in time for sales in the 2010 growing season.

Or how do you see it?

Yes, Peter, we're going to address that in two weeks. I don't mean to keep putting you off, but we would like to be able to provide the full context and we will give you color on what to expect with pharma full year as well as the pattern of decline through the year. So give us a chance to do that in the full context of our expectations for 2010.
Our next question comes from Edward Yang from Oppenheimer. Please go ahead.

Hi, good morning. You showed some pretty nice volume improvement across the board but Ellen, you mentioned that the U.S. has been lagging and that was the only region where volume declines were basically equal to what they were in the second quarter. And I was surprised by that given Cash for Clunker and so on. So which parts of the business in the U.S. kind of held back some of the improvement you've seen in other regions?

Well, you know, the U.S. is a real mix. I mean, ex-ag, sequentially we're up 11%. We were down 17% ex-ag whereas in the second quarter we were down 25. Certainly that improvement is seen through our automotive value chains and through even construction being a little bit stronger. So we're – the U.S. we see as that third quarter's being pretty good considering where we've been in the first half of the year.

Is it just a greater percentage of your commercial construction assets are in the U.S versus other regions? Or I'm thinking more year-over-year in terms of what businesses are still kind of lagging in the U.S?

Well, I think we mentioned that it's the aramids, Nomex and Kevlar are lagging. They didn't go down; they didn't head down from a volume standpoint until very late in the first quarter, early in the second quarter. They're a late cycle business so they are still kind of bouncing along the bottom where we're seeing sequential improvements in other. And the other thing is that military has held off in this last quarter and they weren't at the profile that they've historically been. So it's really those two things that have been an impact there.
And our next question comes from Laurence Alexander from Jefferies. Please go ahead.

Hi, two questions on mix. First, for safety and protection, how much of an improvement in end market demand do you need to get back to your historical high teens margins now that the destocking has ended? And secondly, what flexibility do you have to pull forward PFOA substitutes to affect, to offset any adverse mix effects that might arise there?

Yes, so in Safety & Protection, there's two things. Yeah, the volume needs to come back a bit. But we did a second quarter restructuring on our assets there since they went down late. And they're going to lower the breakeven for those units, so we're not going to need full volume recovery to get back to the kinds of margins that we've come to expect from that group. On PFOA alternatives, we're on track with where our commitments are there. We are active in the market in this area and working to get basically approvals and from the customer bases as quickly as we can as we move out. Obviously, it impacts a lot of different individual products in the – fluoro products in the fluoropolymers and the fluorotelomers area but we're on track for those change overs.

Yeah, again on the pension question, we'll kind of map that out for you on November 3. We know that that's a key question on your mind. But again, rather than give one-offs today, I'd much prefer to give a holistic picture.

Our next question comes from Chris Shaw from Ticonderoga Securities. Please go ahead.

Yeah, good morning. Thanks for taking my question. China GDP – I'm sorry, I kind of missed the question. China GDP, from our economists' standpoint they are projecting it's going to be slightly stronger than this year. So the outlook is, if it's about 8% this year, that next year it will be close to 10 or right around 10%. So everything that we're seeing, and I was in China a couple of weeks ago, everything I experienced when I was over there, talking to government officials, talking to customers was very, very solid on that point.
